{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"isHeader":true,"content":"Preparation","step":0},{"isHeader":false,"content":"To remove flesh from oranges, run a small sharp knife horizontally and vertically across the middle of each orange half, ensuring you do not to pierce the skin. Run the knife all the way around the edge of the flesh, separating the flesh from the pith. Remove flesh using a spoon and your fingers. Set flesh aside to use in future recipes (see Tips). Using your knife or a spoon, scrape off as much pith from the empty orange halves as possible (see Tips). Rest empty orange halves into moulds of a 12-hole muffin tray, ensuring they are sitting upright (see Tips).","step":1},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Place strawberries and 300 g of the apple juice into mixing bowl and blend <b>20 sec\/speed 7<b>.","step":2},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Scrape down sides of mixing bowl with spatula and cook <b>4 min\/100°C\/speed 1<b>.","step":3},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Strain strawberry mixture through a fine-mesh sieve into bowl or jug. Rinse and dry mixing bowl.","step":4},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Weigh strawberry mixture back into mixing bowl and add extra apple juice as needed until the mixture reaches 500 g, then cook <b>4 min\/100°C\/speed 1<b>.","step":5},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Place a bowl onto mixing bowl lid and weigh water into it. Add gelatine to bowl and stir gently until gelatine dissolves completely.","step":6},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Add gelatine mixture to mixing bowl and mix <b>20 sec\/speed 3<b> until combined. Using a large spoon, skim any foam off the top of the jelly and discard.","step":7},{"isHeader":false,"content":"Pour jelly mixture into empty orange halves and place into refrigerator for a minimum of 4 hours or until set.","step":8},{"isHeader":false,"content":"To assemble, cut filled oranges into halves using a sharp knife. Arrange onto a platter and place into refrigerator. Make the sails by threading squares or triangles of coloured paper onto toothpicks. Insert sails into jelly boats just before serving.","step":9}],"usefulItems":"toothpick or wooden skewer, serving platter, large spoon, glass bowl or large jug, 12-hole muffin tray, tooth picks, fine mesh sieve, bowl, refrigerator","id":"r119234","imageLink":"https:\/\/2.bp.blogspot.com\/-QWCf1y6V1cg\/XZWfQ3j29nI\/AAAAAAAAfBU\/iyKJXP56i9k2axT3cpKes3V8YfZqnfj2gCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_rqxYC5dtYuuogilf.png","title":"Strawberry jelly boats","ingredients":[{"isHeader":true,"content":"Ingredients"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"5 oranges, cut into halves"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"250 g strawberries, hulled"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"300 - 500 g apple juice (100%)"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"80 g cold water"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"1 tbsp gelatine powder"}],"nutrition":["per 1 portion","106 kJ \/ 25 kcal","1.8 g","4.5 g","0.1 g"],"hintsAndTricks":["Use the flesh and juice from the oranges to make Orange cups (please refer to the recipe on this recipe chip) or use in smoothies.","The number of \"boats\" you can fill will depend on how much pith is left in your oranges. Each orange half can hold approx. 50-60 g of the jelly mixture.","Instead of using the oranges, omit step 1 and divide jelly mixture between small paper or plastic cups. Proceed as per recipe.","The strawberry jelly recipe was contributed by Louise Keats. The recipe can be found in her book, <em>Something for Everyone.<br><\/em>"],"basicInfo":["easy","20m","4h","10 portions"]}